INSERT INTO dashboard_public.actions ( owner_id, title, slug, url, photo, location, is_approved, is_published, is_private, self_verifiable, is_recurring, limited_to_location, once_per_object, minimum_group_members, start_date, end_date, description, call_to_action, discovery_header, discovery_description, completed_action_text, activity_feed_text, already_completed_action_text, time_required, recurring_interval ) VALUES ('036cf352-3433-5b92-b1fb-123d6f8a974e', 'Planting in the Right Place', inflection.slugify('Planting in the Right Place'), 'https://www.cityplants.org/tree-care/', '{"url":"https://dl.airtable.com/.attachments/327fe720d358027246ef4d06e32ce3ab/d8e8992e/treeplanting1.jpg","filename":"tree planting  1.jpg","size":480145,"mime":"image/jpeg"}'::jsonb, NULL, TRUE, TRUE, FALSE, TRUE, FALSE, FALSE, FALSE, NULL, '2021-02-01T22:37:00.000Z', '2022-08-02T21:37:00.000Z', '## Planning
There are many factors that go into planting a yard tree, so we encourage you to consider all the right conditions for your particular species.

“Right tree” means the species and full-grown size of the tree is best suited for your home and the area you have available to plant the tree. You can reference our Yard Tree List [here](https://www.cityplants.org/yard-tree-species-list/) to determine how tall your new tree will grow and how the species will mature over time. Keep the full-grown size of your tree in mind when finding its spot.

“Right place” means the tree has enough space to grow to its full, mature height, and its root system has the space it needs to grow fully without interfering with surrounding infrastructure or underground pipes or utility lines. Don’t forget to plant to the west or east of your building to help reduce your energy bills and save energy!

## Where Should I Plant My Yard Tree?
It’s best to plant trees a minimum of 15 – 20 feet away from your foundation, to the west, southwest, or east side of your building. 

You can call 811 at least two days before you plant to make sure you won’t run into any gas or utility lines while planting — they’ll come out for free to inspect for you!

If you plant multiple trees, make sure to space them far enough apart. Large trees should be planted at least 30 feet apart. 

Trees throw major shade! As days get hotter and hotter, trees act as natural air conditioners. 

West is best for energy savings, as the trees will shade your home in the hot afternoon sun and save you $$ on your energy bills!

Planting trees on the east side of your home helps shade it from the morning sun (and some energy savings), but planting to the north will not provide much shade at all. 

Video [City Plants #1: Planta Un Árbol](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=AmBzWd0UKHI)', 'Get Prepared', 'Why', 'Where you plant your tree impacts your tree''s health and the benefits it brings you.', 'I''m ready to plant', 'found a great spot to plant a tree!', NULL, '180 seconds'::interval, '0 seconds'::interval);

INSERT INTO dashboard_public.actions ( owner_id, title, slug, url, photo, location, is_approved, is_published, is_private, self_verifiable, is_recurring, limited_to_location, once_per_object, minimum_group_members, start_date, end_date, description, call_to_action, discovery_header, discovery_description, completed_action_text, activity_feed_text, already_completed_action_text, time_required, recurring_interval ) VALUES ('036cf352-3433-5b92-b1fb-123d6f8a974e', 'Planting your Tree', inflection.slugify('Planting your Tree'), 'https://www.cityplants.org/tree-care/', '{"url":"https://dl.airtable.com/.attachments/aa9160bf1dd7d32ab3e12d05f7bdd382/56caac34/home_ourstory.png","filename":"home_ourstory.png","size":1662047,"mime":"image/png"}'::jsonb, NULL, TRUE, TRUE, FALSE, TRUE, FALSE, FALSE, FALSE, NULL, '2021-04-01T22:51:00.000Z', '2022-01-26T22:52:00.000Z', '## Get Prepared
You will need the following tools:
 • Shovel
• Water (hose or bucket)
• Gloves (optional)
• Mulch (optional)
• Stakes, ties, and arbor guard
(optional)

Did you call Dig Alert at 811  to make sure that you don’t have any gas or utility lines where you want to plant.

[Bilingual Tree Planting Guide](https://www.cityplants.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/Yard-Tree-Planting-Guidelines.pdf)


## How
1. DIG: Dig a hole at least twice the width of the tree’s container and just as deep as the soil in the pot. You can use your shovel as a measuring stick!

2. PLACE TREE: 
* Remove the tree from the pot. Avoid damaging the root ball. 
* "Massage” or loosen the roots gently to open them up,  so that they can grow outward and get off to a good start. If there are any large “circling” roots, cut them, as they can actually strangle your new tree. 
* Drop the mycorrhizal tablets in the hole (that came with your tree)
* Place the tree in the hole. 

3. BACKFILL: 
* Refill the hole with soil. Make sure the top of the root ball (where the trunk meets the roots and flares out) is 1 to 2 inches ABOVE the surrounding soil level (if a root ball is below soil level, your tree may die). 
* Lightly poke the soil around the root ball to eliminate all air pockets. 
* Be careful not to pile soil on top of the root ball or against the root flare. You want to keep your root flare exposed so it can breathe!  
* Using native soil is great, as it helps the tree adapt to its new environment. Skip the fertilizer, soil amendment, or potting soil!

4. BUILD A BERM: 
* Form the remaining soil into a berm or a “moat” around the tree. 
* It should look like a donut of soil around the tree, which will ensure that water sinks directly into the tree’s roots.', 'Do it', 'Why', 'In case it''s your first time, here''s our guide to tree planting.', 'I''ve planted a tree', 'planted a tree', NULL, '1800 seconds'::interval, '0 seconds'::interval);

INSERT INTO dashboard_public.actions ( owner_id, title, slug, url, photo, location, is_approved, is_published, is_private, self_verifiable, is_recurring, limited_to_location, once_per_object, minimum_group_members, start_date, end_date, description, call_to_action, discovery_header, discovery_description, completed_action_text, activity_feed_text, already_completed_action_text, time_required, recurring_interval ) VALUES ('036cf352-3433-5b92-b1fb-123d6f8a974e', 'Watering your Tree', inflection.slugify('Watering your Tree'), 'https://www.cityplants.org/tree-care/', '{"url":"https://dl.airtable.com/.attachments/7ea938d42dd310176ffadfcf58b59f83/8dd8845a/untitled-1030copy1.jpg","filename":"untitled-1030 copy 1.jpg","size":312152,"mime":"image/jpeg"}'::jsonb, NULL, TRUE, TRUE, FALSE, TRUE, FALSE, FALSE, FALSE, NULL, '2021-04-01T23:17:00.000Z', '2022-09-13T22:17:00.000Z', '## What
For your tree(s) to survive their first few years of life, they need what we call deep watering, to establish their root systems. Deep watering is the practice of slowly trickling 10-15 gallons of water into the watering basin around the base of a tree. Sprinklers will not sufficiently water young trees. While they are good for grass, we want water to filter deep into the soil around the tree to encourage the roots to grow deeply. 

As a rule of thumb, your tree(s) need 10-15 gallons a week, but during the warmer months, when temperatures can exceed 100 degrees Fahrenheit, you will need to water your trees more frequently. Read on for important tips and tricks!

## How
Fill a 5-gallon bucket of water and gently pour into the tree berm 2-3 times. You can also put a hose on a slow trickle for 1-2 hours. Make sure to water the soil around the tree — not the trunk or the leaves, which can kill your young tree!

How to care for young trees [Video](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qWVOLK7G2m4)

## When should you water your tree?
Water early in the morning or after sunset, when the sun won’t evaporate water as readily.

1ST & 2ND YEAR: Deep water your shade tree once a week with 10-15 gallons. Water your fruit tree 17-20 gallons once a week. During warmer months, you may need to water your tree(s) more frequently. 

3RD YEAR: Deep water every 4-6 weeks during the year, water a little more during the summer. Continue to check the soil for its moisture level if you’re not certain whether or not the tree needs water.

Save Your Trees From Drought [Video](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=BiHmGdUP8hQ)

## TIPS:
Tip 1: If you are ever unsure if you need to water, check the soil! Try this out:
* Dig 2 - 3 inches into the soil around the root ball of your tree and grab a handful of soil.
* Squeeze the soil into a ball. 
* If the soil crumbles, your tree needs more water! 
* If the soil sticks together, your tree has enough moisture. It’s important not to overwater a tree too, because roots need oxygen, just like we do, and when they are too submerged in water, they are not able to breathe. 

Tip 2: A newly planted tree uses the same amount of water as a 5-minute shower each week — Not too much at all! Collect excess water from your shower in a bucket and use it to water your new tree.

Tip 4: Rainwater is precious here. Consider collecting rainwater to water your new tree when seasons permit.

Tip 5: If you water your tree with a hose, time how long it takes to fill a 5-gallon bucket with the hose set on a slow trickle, multiply that by 2-3 times. That is the time you will let your hose run when watering your tree. Make sure that the water does not escape the berm, but stays inside the tree well and soaks deep down into the roots.

Reminder: Trees are like natural air conditioners. The 5-gallon trees you planted will not yield immediate shade. However, planting trees when they are young allows them to establish themselves early, and if planted correctly, they will grow vigorously and eventually help cool both you and your home.
', 'Water', 'Why', 'Turns out, how and when you water your tree is key to its survival.', 'I''ve watered my tree', 'watered their tree', NULL, '300 seconds'::interval, '604800 seconds'::interval);

